vice is connected to the same number of hops (i.e., switches) in the network. This can result in improved predictability on STP blocked ports, as there are fewer hops for traffic to pass through. However, this is not a guaranteed characteristic of spine-and-leaf architectures, as the specific design and implementation will determine the actual behavior.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: What is a characteristic of spine-and-leaf architecture between the option provided below?\nA. Each link between leaf switches allows for higher bandwidth.\nB. It provides greater predictability on STP blocked ports.\nC. It provides variable latency.\nD. Each device is separated by the same number of hops.\nAnswer: I apologize for the confusion. It appears that you have provided a list of options for a multiple-choice question, but have not specified which of the options you are asking about. Could you please clarify your question by specifying which of the provided options you would like to know more about?\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: D is the correct answer\nAnswer: A characteristic of spine-and-leaf architecture is that each link between leaf switches allows for higher bandwidth. In a spine-and-leaf architecture, the spine switches typically have high-bandwidth connections to the leaf switches, which allows for efficient data transfer between the devices connected to the leaf switches. This architecture is commonly used in data center networks to provide a scalable and highly available network design. Other characteristics of spine-and-leaf architecture include greater predictability on STP blocked ports and each device being separated by the same number of hops. It does not provide variable latency.\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: An office has 8 floors with approximately 30-40 users per floor. One subnet must be used. Which command must be configured on the router Switched Virtual\nInterface to use address space efficiently?\nA. ip address 192.168.0.0 255.