ts bonding with us otherwise our sym will die.\nAnswer: Okay, I understand. So to summarize, instead of having a death mechanic for the sym, you want to introduce a poisoning mechanic that will gradually affect the sym's components, starting from the endoskeleton, and spreading to the casing, conn, and biot. The poisoning levels will determine which components need to be replaced, and the quicker we take action, the fewer parts we need to exchange. There will be three levels of poisoning, and if we fix the problem at level 3 or before, we can keep our sym alive with all its bonding with us, otherwise, our sym will die. Is that correct?\n\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\nQuestion: yes\nAnswer: Alright, I have made the necessary changes to the previous concept based on your input. Let me know if you have any other ideas or modifications in mind.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: would this be an unique mechanic?\nAnswer: Yes, this would be a unique mechanic for a game involving creatures or robots. It adds a level of realism to the gameplay and forces players to be mindful of the lifespan and maintenance of their creature. It also adds an element of strategy, as players must weigh the costs and benefits of investing in the repair and replacement of their sym's components versus obtaining a new one.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: lore wise what would have happened is. the people would have noticed that inert to make a more sentient creature, they would have had to increased the organic content of the sym to have more complexity in it. but this resulted to increase of the chance of poisoning because of this fusion of living and non living matter because of which the newer sym's parts should be replaced and stuff unlike the previous generations of syms living in the forest who are still alive after 50 years with just food and water.\nAnswer: That sounds like a plausible explanation for the increased risk of poisoning in the newer syms. It also adds an interesting 