t bitrates as low as 16 kbps.\n3. AAC-HEv2: This is an improved version of HE-AAC that provides better audio quality at lower bitrates.\n4. AAC-LD (Low-Delay): This variant of AAC is designed for real-time communication and has very low latency.\n5. AAC-ELD (Enhanced Low Delay): This variant of AAC is similar to AAC-LD but provides better audio quality and lower latency.\n\nFor online radio broadcasting, AAC-LC is the most commonly used variant as it provides good audio quality at moderate bitrates and is widely supported by devices and streaming platforms.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: How many pages does it have?\nAnswer: Yes, the AES67 standard document includes guidelines and requirements for the implementation of the protocols used in AES67, including RTP, RTCP, SDP, and SAP. These guidelines and requirements ensure interoperability between AES67-compliant devices and networks.\n\nFor example, the AES67 standard defines the payload formats for RTP, specifies the use of RTCP for monitoring and control of the RTP session, and provides guidelines for the use of SDP for session description and announcement. It also specifies the use of SAP for multicast address resolution and session announcement in large-scale deployments.\n\nIn addition to these specific protocol guidelines, the AES67 standard also includes more general requirements for interoperability, such as requirements for clock synchronization and media clock rates.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: are there many difference between the freely draft document and the final one?\nAnswer: The AES67 standard document has 44 pages.\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: The RTP guidelines, in which section it exist in the draft and in the final version?\nAnswer: The freely available draft document and the final AES67 standard document should be quite similar, as the draft document is essentially a public preview of the final standard. However, it's possible that there may be some minor differences