ch by keeping private network addresses hidden from the Internet.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: Which WAN access technology is preferred for a small office / home office architecture?\nA. broadband cable access\nB. frame-relay packet switching\nC. dedicated point-to-point leased line\nD. Integrated Services Digital Network switching\nAnswer: Broadband cable access is often preferred for a small office/home office (SOHO) architecture because it is generally less expensive and more flexible than other options. It can also provide high-speed Internet access, making it suitable for small businesses with high-bandwidth requirements. Other options, such as frame-relay packet switching and dedicated point-to-point leased lines, tend to be more expensive and may not be necessary for a small office or home office. Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN) switching is also generally not a suitable option for a SOHO architecture because it is outdated and has been replaced by newer technologies.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: Which two WAN architecture options help a business scalability and reliability for the network? (Choose two.)\nA. asychronous routing\nB. single-homed branches\nC. dual-homed branches\nD. static routing\nE. dynamic routing\nAnswer: C. dual-homed branches\nE. dynamic routing\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: What is the binary pattern of unique ipv6 unique local address?\nA. 00000000\nB. 11111100\nC. 11111111\nD. 11111101\nAnswer: The binary pattern of a unique local IPv6 address is 1111 110x, where the x is a variable that can be either 0 or 1. The unique local address is a type of IPv6 address that is intended for use within a single organization and is not globally routable. It is similar to the IPv4 private address space, which is used for communication within a private network. Unique local addresses are identified by the first 7 bits, which are set to 1111 110 in binary. The 8th bit is variable and can be either 0 or 1.\n<|im_